### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

v17+

### Description

Current defer semantics permit component loading based on conditions set in `when` which include state bound to the component, as described in the RFC [here](https://github.com/angular/angular/discussions/50716#discussioncomment-6200144). 

Example: 

```
@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    @defer (when whenSuccess()) {
      {{ whenSuccess().foo }}
    } @placeholder (minimum 2s) {
      <p><strong>this is a placeholder...</strong></p>
    }
  `,
})
export class App implements OnInit {
  whenSuccess = signal<any>(undefined);

  ngOnInit() {
    setTimeout(() => {
      this.whenSuccess.set({ foo: 'a', bar: 'b' });
    }, 3_000);
  }
}
```

There are two shortcomings of the existing implementation from a devex perspective:

1. The responsibility of displaying error state requires leaning on additional control-flow syntax within the template.
Example: 

```
@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    @defer (when whenSuccess()) {
      @if (!whenSuccess().error) {
        <div>
          Success
        </div>
      } @else {
        <div>An error occured</div>
      }
    } @placeholder (minimum 2s) {
      <p><strong>this is a placeholder...</strong></p>
    } @error {
      <div>Failed to load the defered js</div>
    }
  `,
})

```

2. `} error {}` is not intuitive; `error` should simply allow for user-defined error-states in addition to failing to fetch scripts.


### Proposed solution

Proposed solution is to allow the error statement to utilize `when` similar to `defer`'s `when` statement:

```
@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    @defer (when whenSuccess()) {
    } @placeholder (minimum 2s) {
      <p><strong>this is a placeholder...</strong></p>
    } @error (whenSuccess().error) {
      <div>{{ whenSuccess().error }}</div>
    }
  `,
})
```

### Alternatives considered

The alternative solution to use `@if {} @else {}` is explored above.

### Description

Angular provides a [DOCUMENT](https://angular.io/api/common/DOCUMENT) DI token that returns either the browsers `document` or an instance of `domino` for use on the server side.

Therefor it is not possible to use `window.getComputedStyle()` or react to `window.resize` event.

### Proposed solution

Angular should also provide a `WINDOW` DI token returning either `window` or the domino window instance.

### Workaround
We can create our own DI token that makes use of the `DOCUMENT` DI token created by Angular:

```
import {inject, InjectionToken} from '@angular/core';
import {DOCUMENT} from '@angular/common';

export const WINDOW = new InjectionToken<Window>('Global window object', {
  factory: () => {
    const document = inject(DOCUMENT);
    return document.defaultView!;
  }
});
```

### Is this a regression?
No

### Description

When i apply the following css style 

.mat-mdc-form-field.mat-primary {
